-- 14-dependency-graph-builder-frames.cell — full eval-one execution trace
--
-- Ready set analysis:
--   codebase: all givens have ≡ → READY
--   identify-modules: needs codebase→description → BLOCKED
--   spawn-dependency-analyzers: needs identify-modules→modules → BLOCKED
--   analyzer-*: spawned dynamically → BLOCKED
--   build-adjacency: needs analyzer-*→depends-on → BLOCKED
--   validate-acyclicity: needs build-adjacency→internal-edges → BLOCKED
--   spawn-sub-module-analyzers: needs build-adjacency→internal-edges → BLOCKED
--   sub-analyzer-*: spawned dynamically → BLOCKED
--   assemble-full-graph: needs everything → BLOCKED
--
-- Ready set: { codebase }
-- Structure: codebase → identify-modules → spawn-analyzers → [analyzer-1..N]
--            → build-adjacency → { validate-acyclicity, spawn-sub-module-analyzers }
--            → [sub-analyzer-1..N] → assemble-full-graph

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- frame 0: codebase
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ codebase
  given description ≡ "Gas Town — a multi-agent workspace manager with: mayor (coordinator that dispatches work and handles escalations), witness (monitors polecat lifecycle, health checks, nudges stuck agents), refinery (bisecting merge queue that merges polecat branches), beads (Dolt-backed issue tracking with dependency DAG), gt CLI (orchestration commands: prime, hook, done, mail, escalate), dolt (SQL data layer providing versioned database for beads and agent state)"
  yield description ≡ "Gas Town — a multi-agent workspace manager with: mayor (coordinator that dispatches work and handles escalations), witness (monitors polecat lifecycle, health checks, nudges stuck agents), refinery (bisecting merge queue that merges polecat branches), beads (Dolt-backed issue tracking with dependency DAG), gt CLI (orchestration commands: prime, hook, done, mail, escalate), dolt (SQL data layer providing versioned database for beads and agent state)"

  ⊨ description names at least 4 distinct modules → ✓ (6: mayor, witness, refinery, beads, gt, dolt)

-- Ready set after frame 0: { identify-modules }

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- frame 1: identify-modules
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ identify-modules
  given codebase→description ≡ "Gas Town — a multi-agent workspace manager with..."
  yield modules[], module-descriptions[]

  ∴ Read the description and identify all top-level modules...

-- LLM evaluation:
-- The description explicitly names 6 components. Let me verify each is a
-- distinct module with a single responsibility:
--
-- 1. mayor — coordinates agents, dispatches work, handles escalations
-- 2. witness — monitors polecats, health checks, nudges stuck agents
-- 3. refinery — merge queue, bisects failures, merges branches
-- 4. beads — issue tracking, dependency DAG, Dolt-backed storage
-- 5. gt — CLI orchestration, user-facing commands
-- 6. dolt — SQL data layer, versioned database
--
-- Are there implicit modules? The "polecat" is an agent type, not a module.
-- "mail" is a feature within gt, not a separate module. 6 modules is complete.

  yield modules ≡ ["mayor", "witness", "refinery", "beads", "gt", "dolt"]

  yield module-descriptions ≡ [
    "mayor: Global coordinator — dispatches work to polecats, handles escalations, manages town-level state",
    "witness: Polecat lifecycle manager — monitors health, detects stuck agents, nudges or restarts, verifies completions",
    "refinery: Bisecting merge queue — receives MRs from polecats, runs gates, bisects on failure, merges to main",
    "beads: Issue tracking system — Dolt-backed, dependency-aware, prefix-routed, tracks issues/mail/molecules",
    "gt: CLI orchestration tool — user-facing commands (prime, hook, done, mail, escalate), wraps lower-level tools",
    "dolt: SQL data layer — versioned database server, provides storage for beads and agent state"
  ]

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ length(modules) ≥ 4 → ✓ (6)
--   ⊨ each module has single responsibility → ✓
--   ⊨ modules are non-overlapping → ✓

-- Ready set after frame 1: { spawn-dependency-analyzers }

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- frame 2: spawn-dependency-analyzers
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢⊢ spawn-dependency-analyzers
  given identify-modules→modules ≡ ["mayor", "witness", "refinery", "beads", "gt", "dolt"]
  given identify-modules→module-descriptions ≡ [6 descriptions]
  given §dependency-analyzer-template
  yield §analyzer-cells ≡ [§analyzer-1, §analyzer-2, §analyzer-3, §analyzer-4, §analyzer-5, §analyzer-6]

  ⊨ one analyzer cell per module → ✓ (6 cells for 6 modules)

-- 6 cells spawned. All READY (each has module-name, module-desc, all-modules bound).
-- Ready set: { analyzer-1, analyzer-2, analyzer-3, analyzer-4, analyzer-5, analyzer-6 }

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- frames 3-8: analyzer-1 through analyzer-6
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

-- --- frame 3: analyzer-1 (mayor) ---

⊢ analyzer-1
  given module-name ≡ "mayor"
  given module-desc ≡ "Global coordinator — dispatches work to polecats, handles escalations, manages town-level state"
  given all-modules ≡ ["mayor", "witness", "refinery", "beads", "gt", "dolt"]
  yield depends-on[], dependency-types[], rationale

  ∴ Identify dependencies of mayor...

-- LLM evaluation:
-- Mayor dispatches work → needs to read issues from beads (what work exists).
-- Mayor handles escalations → receives escalation messages via beads/mail.
-- Mayor manages town-level state → stores state in dolt.
-- Mayor communicates with witness → sends nudges, reads health status.
-- Mayor does NOT directly use gt (gt calls mayor, not the other way).
-- Mayor does NOT directly use refinery (refinery is autonomous).

  yield depends-on ≡ ["beads", "dolt", "witness"]
  yield dependency-types ≡ ["internal", "internal", "internal"]
  yield rationale ≡ "mayor → beads: reads issues to dispatch work, receives escalations. mayor → dolt: stores town-level state (agent registry, dispatch history). mayor → witness: reads polecat health status, sends coordination nudges."

  ⊨ each dependency classified → ✓
  ⊨ no self-dependencies → ✓
  ⊨ rationale explains each → ✓

-- --- frame 4: analyzer-2 (witness) ---

⊢ analyzer-2
  given module-name ≡ "witness"
  given module-desc ≡ "Polecat lifecycle manager — monitors health, detects stuck agents, nudges or restarts, verifies completions"
  given all-modules ≡ ["mayor", "witness", "refinery", "beads", "gt", "dolt"]
  yield depends-on[], dependency-types[], rationale

-- LLM evaluation:
-- Witness monitors polecats → reads agent state from dolt.
-- Witness creates/updates issues → writes to beads (hook management, status updates).
-- Witness escalates to mayor → sends escalations.
-- Witness uses gt commands internally? No — witness IS a gt-level agent, it
-- uses beads and dolt directly, not through gt CLI.
-- Witness does NOT depend on refinery (separate concerns).

  yield depends-on ≡ ["beads", "dolt", "mayor"]
  yield dependency-types ≡ ["internal", "internal", "internal"]
  yield rationale ≡ "witness → beads: reads/writes polecat hook status, updates bead lifecycle. witness → dolt: reads agent state, session records. witness → mayor: escalates unresolvable issues, reports polecat deaths."

-- NOTE: witness → mayor AND mayor → witness. This looks like a CYCLE.
-- We'll check in validate-acyclicity.

-- --- frame 5: analyzer-3 (refinery) ---

⊢ analyzer-3
  given module-name ≡ "refinery"
  given module-desc ≡ "Bisecting merge queue — receives MRs from polecats, runs gates, bisects on failure, merges to main"
  given all-modules ≡ ["mayor", "witness", "refinery", "beads", "gt", "dolt"]
  yield depends-on[], dependency-types[], rationale

-- LLM evaluation:
-- Refinery receives MRs → reads MR beads from beads.
-- Refinery runs git operations → uses git directly (external).
-- Refinery closes issues after merge → writes to beads.
-- Refinery reports results → could notify witness or mayor, but primarily
-- operates autonomously. The notification is via beads (closing the MR bead).
-- Refinery does NOT depend on mayor or witness directly.

  yield depends-on ≡ ["beads", "dolt", "git"]
  yield dependency-types ≡ ["internal", "internal", "external"]
  yield rationale ≡ "refinery → beads: reads MR beads from merge queue, closes issues after merge. refinery → dolt: beads storage layer (transitive through beads, but also direct for merge state). refinery → git: executes git merge, rebase, push operations (external dependency)."

-- --- frame 6: analyzer-4 (beads) ---

⊢ analyzer-4
  given module-name ≡ "beads"
  given module-desc ≡ "Issue tracking system — Dolt-backed, dependency-aware, prefix-routed, tracks issues/mail/molecules"
  given all-modules ≡ ["mayor", "witness", "refinery", "beads", "gt", "dolt"]
  yield depends-on[], dependency-types[], rationale

-- LLM evaluation:
-- Beads stores data in dolt → primary dependency.
-- Beads does NOT depend on mayor, witness, refinery, or gt.
-- Beads is a LIBRARY/SERVICE that others call into, not the other way around.
-- It's a data layer that sits on top of dolt.

  yield depends-on ≡ ["dolt"]
  yield dependency-types ≡ ["internal"]
  yield rationale ≡ "beads → dolt: all issue/mail/molecule data stored in Dolt databases. Beads is a data access layer over Dolt — it cannot function without the Dolt server."

-- KEY: beads has only ONE dependency. It's close to the bottom of the DAG.

-- --- frame 7: analyzer-5 (gt) ---

⊢ analyzer-5
  given module-name ≡ "gt"
  given module-desc ≡ "CLI orchestration tool — user-facing commands (prime, hook, done, mail, escalate), wraps lower-level tools"
  given all-modules ≡ ["mayor", "witness", "refinery", "beads", "gt", "dolt"]
  yield depends-on[], dependency-types[], rationale

-- LLM evaluation:
-- gt is the CLI FACADE. It wraps everything.
-- gt prime → reads role context, uses beads for state.
-- gt hook → reads from beads (hook status).
-- gt done → pushes branch (git), creates MR bead (beads), notifies witness.
-- gt mail → sends via beads mail system.
-- gt escalate → creates escalation bead, notifies mayor.
-- gt depends on beads (data), mayor (escalations), witness (notifications),
-- and git (external, for branch operations).
-- gt does NOT depend on refinery (gt done submits TO refinery, but through beads).
-- gt does NOT directly depend on dolt (uses beads as abstraction layer).

  yield depends-on ≡ ["beads", "mayor", "witness", "git"]
  yield dependency-types ≡ ["internal", "internal", "internal", "external"]
  yield rationale ≡ "gt → beads: all data operations (hook, mail, issues, molecules). gt → mayor: escalation delivery, dispatch queries. gt → witness: completion notifications (gt done notifies witness). gt → git: branch operations (push, checkout, rebase)."

-- gt is the TOP of the dependency chain. It depends on almost everything.

-- --- frame 8: analyzer-6 (dolt) ---

⊢ analyzer-6
  given module-name ≡ "dolt"
  given module-desc ≡ "SQL data layer — versioned database server, provides storage for beads and agent state"
  given all-modules ≡ ["mayor", "witness", "refinery", "beads", "gt", "dolt"]
  yield depends-on[], dependency-types[], rationale

-- LLM evaluation:
-- Dolt is the data foundation. It depends on NOTHING internal.
-- External: MySQL wire protocol (how clients connect), filesystem (storage).

  yield depends-on ≡ ["mysql-protocol", "filesystem"]
  yield dependency-types ≡ ["external", "external"]
  yield rationale ≡ "dolt → mysql-protocol: serves SQL over MySQL wire protocol (external standard). dolt → filesystem: stores versioned data on disk. No internal Gas Town dependencies — dolt is the foundation layer."

-- dolt is the ROOT of the DAG. Zero internal dependencies.

-- All 6 analyzers complete.
-- Ready set after frames 3-8: { build-adjacency }

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- frame 9: build-adjacency
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ build-adjacency
  given analyzer-1→depends-on ≡ ["beads", "dolt", "witness"]
  given analyzer-1→dependency-types ≡ ["internal", "internal", "internal"]
  given analyzer-2→depends-on ≡ ["beads", "dolt", "mayor"]
  given analyzer-2→dependency-types ≡ ["internal", "internal", "internal"]
  given analyzer-3→depends-on ≡ ["beads", "dolt", "git"]
  given analyzer-3→dependency-types ≡ ["internal", "internal", "external"]
  given analyzer-4→depends-on ≡ ["dolt"]
  given analyzer-4→dependency-types ≡ ["internal"]
  given analyzer-5→depends-on ≡ ["beads", "mayor", "witness", "git"]
  given analyzer-5→dependency-types ≡ ["internal", "internal", "internal", "external"]
  given analyzer-6→depends-on ≡ ["mysql-protocol", "filesystem"]
  given analyzer-6→dependency-types ≡ ["external", "external"]
  given identify-modules→modules ≡ ["mayor", "witness", "refinery", "beads", "gt", "dolt"]
  yield edges[], internal-edges[], external-deps[]

  ∴ Collect all dependencies and build the adjacency list...

-- LLM evaluation:
-- All edges (source → target):
-- mayor → beads (I), mayor → dolt (I), mayor → witness (I)
-- witness → beads (I), witness → dolt (I), witness → mayor (I)
-- refinery → beads (I), refinery → dolt (I), refinery → git (E)
-- beads → dolt (I)
-- gt → beads (I), gt → mayor (I), gt → witness (I), gt → git (E)
-- dolt → mysql-protocol (E), dolt → filesystem (E)

  yield edges ≡ [
    { source: "mayor", target: "beads" },
    { source: "mayor", target: "dolt" },
    { source: "mayor", target: "witness" },
    { source: "witness", target: "beads" },
    { source: "witness", target: "dolt" },
    { source: "witness", target: "mayor" },
    { source: "refinery", target: "beads" },
    { source: "refinery", target: "dolt" },
    { source: "refinery", target: "git" },
    { source: "beads", target: "dolt" },
    { source: "gt", target: "beads" },
    { source: "gt", target: "mayor" },
    { source: "gt", target: "witness" },
    { source: "gt", target: "git" },
    { source: "dolt", target: "mysql-protocol" },
    { source: "dolt", target: "filesystem" }
  ]

  yield internal-edges ≡ [
    { source: "mayor", target: "beads" },
    { source: "mayor", target: "dolt" },
    { source: "mayor", target: "witness" },
    { source: "witness", target: "beads" },
    { source: "witness", target: "dolt" },
    { source: "witness", target: "mayor" },
    { source: "refinery", target: "beads" },
    { source: "refinery", target: "dolt" },
    { source: "beads", target: "dolt" },
    { source: "gt", target: "beads" },
    { source: "gt", target: "mayor" },
    { source: "gt", target: "witness" }
  ]

  yield external-deps ≡ [
    { module: "refinery", external: "git" },
    { module: "gt", external: "git" },
    { module: "dolt", external: "mysql-protocol" },
    { module: "dolt", external: "filesystem" }
  ]

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ every edge has valid source and target → ✓
--   ⊨ internal-edges is subset of edges → ✓ (12 of 16)
--   ⊨ no duplicate edges → ✓

-- CRITICAL OBSERVATION: mayor → witness AND witness → mayor.
-- This is a CYCLE in the internal edge set. The acyclicity oracle
-- is about to FAIL.

-- Ready set after frame 9: { validate-acyclicity, spawn-sub-module-analyzers }
-- Both can proceed — validate needs internal-edges, spawn needs internal-edges + modules.

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- frame 10: validate-acyclicity
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ validate-acyclicity
  given build-adjacency→internal-edges ≡ [12 internal edges]
  given identify-modules→modules ≡ ["mayor", "witness", "refinery", "beads", "gt", "dolt"]
  yield is-acyclic, topological-order[], cycle-description

  ∴ Check if the internal dependency graph is acyclic using topological sort...

-- LLM evaluation:
-- Running Kahn's algorithm (topological sort via in-degree):
--
-- Adjacency (internal only):
--   gt → {beads, mayor, witness}
--   mayor → {beads, dolt, witness}
--   witness → {beads, dolt, mayor}
--   refinery → {beads, dolt}
--   beads → {dolt}
--   dolt → {}
--
-- In-degrees:
--   dolt: 4 (from mayor, witness, refinery, beads)
--   beads: 4 (from mayor, witness, refinery, gt)
--   mayor: 2 (from witness, gt)
--   witness: 2 (from mayor, gt)
--   refinery: 0
--   gt: 0
--
-- Step 1: Queue = {refinery, gt} (in-degree 0)
-- Process refinery: remove edges refinery→beads, refinery→dolt
--   beads in-degree: 3, dolt in-degree: 3
-- Process gt: remove edges gt→beads, gt→mayor, gt→witness
--   beads in-degree: 2, mayor in-degree: 1, witness in-degree: 1
--
-- Step 2: Queue = {} — no node has in-degree 0!
--   mayor in-degree: 1 (from witness)
--   witness in-degree: 1 (from mayor)
--   beads in-degree: 2
--   dolt in-degree: 3
--
-- STUCK. 4 nodes remain. mayor and witness have mutual dependency.
--
-- CYCLE DETECTED: mayor → witness → mayor

  yield is-acyclic ≡ false
  yield topological-order ≡ []
  yield cycle-description ≡ "CYCLE: mayor → witness → mayor. The mayor depends on witness (reads health status, sends coordination nudges) and witness depends on mayor (escalates unresolvable issues, reports polecat deaths). This is a mutual dependency — neither can be initialized without the other. Partial order achievable: [gt, refinery] → ... but mayor and witness form a strongly connected component."

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ is-acyclic ∈ { true, false } → ✓ (false)
--   ⊨ if not is-acyclic then cycle-description names the cycle → ✓

-- THE DAG IS NOT A DAG. The mayor↔witness cycle breaks acyclicity.
-- This is a REAL architectural finding — not a trace artifact.
-- In Gas Town, mayor and witness have a bidirectional communication channel
-- (mail, nudges) that creates a structural cycle.
--
-- ARCHITECTURAL INSIGHT: The cycle exists because mayor and witness are
-- PEERS, not layers. In a strict layered architecture, information flows
-- one way. Mayor and witness are co-dependent monitors that need each
-- other for different failure modes. Breaking the cycle would require:
-- (a) introducing a shared event bus they both subscribe to, or
-- (b) making one subordinate to the other (witness reports TO mayor only,
--     mayor never queries witness directly).

-- Ready set: { spawn-sub-module-analyzers } (can proceed despite cycle)

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- frames 11-12: spawn and execute sub-module analyzers
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢⊢ spawn-sub-module-analyzers
  given build-adjacency→internal-edges ≡ [12 edges]
  given identify-modules→modules ≡ ["mayor", "witness", "refinery", "beads", "gt", "dolt"]
  given §sub-module-analyzer-template
  yield §sub-analyzer-cells ≡ [§sub-analyzer-1 .. §sub-analyzer-6]

  ⊨ one sub-analyzer per module → ✓

-- 6 sub-analyzer cells spawned. All READY.

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- frames 13-18: sub-analyzer-1 through sub-analyzer-6
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

