  yield full-dag, layer-count, total-nodes, total-edges, summary

  ∴ Assemble the complete two-level dependency graph...

-- LLM evaluation:
-- Layer assignment (partial — cycle prevents full topological sort):
--
-- Layer 0 (no internal deps): dolt
-- Layer 1 (depends only on layer 0): beads
-- Layer 2 (depends on layers 0-1): refinery
-- Layer ?: mayor and witness — CYCLIC, cannot be cleanly layered.
--   If we collapse {mayor, witness} into a single SCC:
--   Layer 2: {mayor, witness} (both depend on beads, dolt)
--   Layer 3: refinery (depends on beads, dolt — same as layer 2, could be 2)
-- Layer 3: gt (depends on beads, mayor, witness)
--
-- Adjusted layers treating {mayor, witness} as one unit:
-- Layer 0: dolt
-- Layer 1: beads
-- Layer 2: {mayor↔witness}, refinery
-- Layer 3: gt

  yield full-dag ≡ "
GAS TOWN DEPENDENCY GRAPH
═════════════════════════

Layer 3: gt [command-parser → session-manager → mail-client]
  │  depends on: beads, mayor, witness, (ext: git)
  │
Layer 2: mayor↔witness (CYCLIC — strongly connected component)
  │  mayor [dispatcher → escalation-handler → state-manager]
  │    depends on: beads, dolt, witness
  │  witness [health-monitor → nudge-engine → lifecycle-manager]
  │    depends on: beads, dolt, mayor
  │
  │  refinery [queue-manager → gate-runner → {bisector, merger}]
  │    depends on: beads, dolt, (ext: git)
  │
Layer 1: beads [routing → issue-store ← dependency-engine]
  │  depends on: dolt
  │
Layer 0: dolt [sql-engine → {storage-layer, version-control}]
    depends on: (ext: mysql-protocol, filesystem)

EXTERNAL DEPENDENCIES: git (refinery, gt), mysql-protocol (dolt), filesystem (dolt)

⚠ CYCLE: mayor ↔ witness (mutual dependency)
  All sub-modules internally acyclic."

  yield layer-count ≡ 4
  yield total-nodes ≡ 24
  yield total-edges ≡ 30

  yield summary ≡ "Two-level dependency graph: 6 top-level modules with 18 sub-modules = 24 total nodes. 12 inter-module edges + 18 intra-module edges = 30 total edges. 4 layers from dolt (foundation) to gt (facade). CYCLE DETECTED: mayor ↔ witness form a strongly connected component — they are peer monitors that need each other. All 6 modules are internally acyclic. 4 external dependencies: git (used by refinery and gt), mysql-protocol and filesystem (used by dolt). The architecture is almost a clean layered DAG — the single cycle between mayor and witness is the only structural defect."

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ full-dag includes both levels → ✓ (modules + sub-modules shown)
--   ⊨ layer-count ≥ 2 → ✓ (4 layers)
--   ⊨ summary describes structure and findings → ✓

-- COMPLETE: 20 eval-one frames (0-19). 12 cells spawned (6 analyzers + 6 sub-analyzers).
-- The graph builder found a REAL architectural cycle (mayor↔witness),
-- validated internal acyclicity of all 6 modules, and produced a layered
-- dependency visualization.

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- OBSERVATIONS
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢= obs-cycle-found
  given §14-dependency-graph-builder
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "THE DAG ISN'T A DAG: validate-acyclicity returned is-acyclic=false. The mayor↔witness cycle is a genuine architectural finding — they are mutual monitors. Mayor dispatches to polecats and reads witness health reports. Witness monitors polecats and escalates to mayor. Neither can be initialized without the other. In Cell terms: the oracle CAUGHT a structural defect. The ⊨ 'is the graph acyclic?' was answered honestly (false), not papered over. This is what oracles are FOR — structural validation that catches real problems."

⊢= obs-recursive-graph-construction
  given §14-dependency-graph-builder
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "TWO-LEVEL RECURSION VIA ⊢⊢: Level 1 spawned 6 analyzer cells (one per module). Level 2 spawned 6 sub-analyzer cells (one per module's internals). The same pattern — spawn per entity, analyze, collect — repeated at both levels. Cell's ⊢⊢ makes this structural recursion NATURAL. The spawner doesn't need to know how many entities there are — it spawns one cell per item in the input list. The graph BUILDS ITSELF as cells execute. This is graph construction via frontier growth, not procedural iteration."

⊢= obs-scc-as-architectural-smell
  given §14-dependency-graph-builder
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "STRONGLY CONNECTED COMPONENTS ARE ARCHITECTURAL SMELLS: mayor and witness forming an SCC means they can't be deployed, tested, or reasoned about independently. In practice, Gas Town handles this via message-passing (mail/nudges are async, no synchronous calls), which HIDES the cycle at runtime but doesn't eliminate it structurally. The fix would be: extract the shared state into a separate module (e.g., 'agent-registry' that both read from), breaking the direct dependency. The graph builder identified the problem; fixing it is architectural design work."

⊢= obs-layers-emerge-from-deps
  given §14-dependency-graph-builder
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "LAYERED ARCHITECTURE EMERGED FROM DEPENDENCY ANALYSIS: nobody DESIGNED the 4-layer structure (dolt → beads → {mayor, witness, refinery} → gt). It emerged from the dependency edges. dolt has zero internal deps → layer 0. beads depends only on dolt → layer 1. The layers are a CONSEQUENCE of the dependency DAG, not an input to it. Cell's collect-from-all pattern (given analyzer-*→depends-on) lets build-adjacency see the full picture that no individual analyzer can see. The global view reveals structure invisible at the local level."

⊢= obs-internal-vs-external
  given §14-dependency-graph-builder
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "INTERNAL/EXTERNAL CLASSIFICATION DEFINES THE SYSTEM BOUNDARY: 12 internal edges (within Gas Town) vs 4 external (git, mysql-protocol, filesystem). The external deps are INTERFACES — they define where Gas Town meets the outside world. git is used by refinery and gt (branch operations). dolt uses mysql-protocol (how clients connect) and filesystem (where data lives). This classification is itself a dependency graph insight: the external deps are the PORTS in a ports-and-adapters architecture. Cell made this visible by having each analyzer classify its own deps."
